Scientists have found a way to find their star relatives
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz, have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneities in star clusters.
The discovery is expected to allow researchers to search for related stars, which are from the same cluster.
The authors published their findings in the journal Nature, and a brief review of the findings can be found on the university's website.
The reason for the similar chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in the gas clouds that preceded the formation of stars.
Even if the newborn star leaves the cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of its relative stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of its relatives in the cluster.
The results of the astrophysicists' simulations show that such differences should not occur.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to simulate two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
Over millions of years, this object under its own gravity transforms into a cluster, where protostars begin to form.
The scientists added markers to the initial gas streams and found that the rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieved a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
Astrophysicists believe that their research proves that it is possible to look for relative stars by their chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
