Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill that would protect the organization of unions as a civil right.
"Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs", says Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota who is a co-chair of the Progressive Caucus.
That's why I'm proud to introduce the Extension of Workers' Rights Act alongside the symbol of the civil rights movement, John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal rights to discriminate against trade unions as it does against other forms of discrimination, while stopping the forces of trade union opponents.
Amending the Labor Relations Act to allow workers facing discrimination for union membership to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation and fines - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it's certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis, and the co-authors of the bill are proposing is to recall a very American idea.
Despite the attacks that unions have been subjected to in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country - Americans once supported countries around the world in adopting, expanding, and respecting labor rights.
There was a time, remembered by millions of Americans, when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country pass a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hideki Tojo was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions play a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, and to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed".
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations for the purpose of protecting and improving labour and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and to every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to restrict this right will not have legal force; measures aimed at these ends will be declared unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chairwoman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations as a world treaty in 1948, Roosevelt and the framers included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect his interests".
For generations, Americans have taken it as a basic tenet that labor rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize unions - and to have those unions participate as equal partners in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - should be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is indeed wise to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living for millions, unions have miraculously created a market for industry and lifted an entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against trade union organisations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that historically enlarged America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge is temporarily blocking a law that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the passage of a Louisiana law that his supporters say will likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginald in June and was scheduled to go into effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have a license to see patients in a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that for now, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authorization.
"The plaintiffs will be permitted to operate legally while continuing the proceedings for their authorization", Judge John deGravells wrote in his decision.
The hearing will be scheduled within the month in which the judge will render a more permanent ruling under this law.
Abortion rights advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to get hospital authorization.
"Today's decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a treacherous law that seeks to take away their health and rights", said Nancy Northup, president and CEO of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit to halt the law on behalf of three of the state's five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics, who were not plaintiffs in the case and had also applied for admission powers.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed such laws, and courts recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in that state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that the laws on admission authority impose medically unnecessary restrictions on doctors.
Opponents of abortion object that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admission authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights reports.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing the procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticising the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission authority await a decision.
What will the introduction of quotas for domestic products lead to ?
At least half of the products in the range of trade networks should be Russian, says Oleg Nilov, a member of the State Duma from the "Justiceful Russia" faction.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, writes the newspaper "Izvestia".
The document will be further detailed to avoid possible inconvenience to the buyers.
For the rest of the products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic producers", - Nilov told the publication.
Along with amendments to the article "On the basis of state regulation of trade activity in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for the introduction of changes to the Tax Code, establishing a reduced rate of VAT of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in retail chains is part of a package of incentives for Russian manufacturers.
There will be several times more domestic goods on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to the lawyer of the company "Taxman", member of the independent expert center "Public Duma" Sergei Litvinenko, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industry, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
The plus is farmers, small shops.
They'll be able to sell more, which means that the profits will increase.
They will also have the right to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, who will be forced to buy their products.
Russian manufacturers will be able to increase their activity and sales, which will lead to higher taxes than before.
It will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will start to expand, some will develop faster, it will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, but not immediately", the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break into local shops due to the high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now, with the embargo, that niche is free and we can breathe a sigh of relief.
But we should not forget that after all the necessary harmonization and sanitary checks, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, now is the "silent moment", when the old players have left and the new ones have not yet come.
Almost a month later, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the increase in the prices of ready-made products", - told Aif.ru the first Vice-President of the Russian public organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors", Tamara Kasyanova.
The idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will definitely help to secure the sector to local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, not with goods that are cheaper due to subsidies from another state.
In other words, the battle for the buyer will be between companies operating under the same industry laws.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian producers are not able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots in all articles.
And in this situation, the retail chains will have to "pull" the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
This has led to growing concerns that poor-quality goods will be sold.
Perhaps foreign products with broken labels will be delivered under the guise of products produced in Russia", the expert adds.
The negative impact of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large trade networks, especially those which are more profitable in cooperating with importers.
It is logical that foreign suppliers would suffer as well, since demand for their products would decline.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods may also affect consumers.
The fact is that some Russian-made products may be inferior in quality to imported counterparts, while stores will be able to raise prices for the latter as a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, which was forgotten in the early 2000s, was revived by economists in February this year due to the ruble's continuing devaluation.
Now, in the face of the difficult relations with the West, the question of abandoning imported products is even more urgent.
The law is designed to oblige retailers to consider domestic manufacturers when forming orders for suppliers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the way of import substitution, and the production planning system for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time", - says deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective in those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example in the dairy sector, where imports accounted for 25%.
Our farmers are actually capable of completely filling the shelves of Russian stores.
Meat production could also be given a boost.
As you know, the largest share of imports remains in beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% of the production is still Russian", - says Kasyanova.
Experts believe that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will facilitate import substitution and may accelerate this process.
However, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, as it requires a set of measures, Litvinenko believes.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported from abroad, which means that there will be no full import substitution, but significant steps will be taken in this direction.
It is not enough to set quotas, we must also establish domestic production in order to meet these quotas.
These quotas will provide just such guarantees", the expert states.
Late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more than in urban areas.
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have released a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who practice abortion in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those who live in urban areas.
Researchers analyzed the medical records of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, and found that only 35 percent survived five years after the diagnosis.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research reported that those living in the regions and remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
NEW RESEARCH: New drugs may slow down lung and ovarian cancer
The researchers tracked the women's medical trajectory over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that a woman's age at diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current illnesses, and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had advanced cancer at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in the regions or remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside of urban areas are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that a late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"The best way to treat this disease is by surgeons who specialize in gynecologic oncology, and they are mostly in big cities", she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of out-of-home services, which will allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people receiving treatment far from their home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Neve, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
