Inflation is out of the holiday.
Will Russians feel the price rise
As a result of cross-border sanctions imposed by Russia and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not fit into the forecasts of the authorities, analysts of VTB Capital are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed effects of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflation shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast by the Ministry of Economic Development, inflation will be 6.5-7.5% in 2014, and even lower - 6.5% next year.
However, according to the Kommersant, the IED should make "small but fundamental" adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast for 2017 this week.
According to the publication, the agency may lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zero growth in the income of the population.
The forecast suggested that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation would be in effect for a year - until August 2015.
How could inflation be expected to be so high in such a situation?
The current situation suggests a one-time shock, but the downward trend of inflation will not change", the newspaper's source in the Ministry of Finance said.
Economists at VTB Capital do not share the government's financial-economic bloc's expectations regarding inflation and predict price growth of 8% in 2014.
The main effect of the food bans will come together with the possible introduction of sales tax (STS) in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
The inflation peak of 9% will fall in February, after which the annual price growth rate will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week, Rosstat released the first inflationary results since the Russian Federation imposed "accurate sanctions".
AI.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, head of the analytical department of AForex FC:
Prices are already rising in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, as socially significant products became more expensive, the government was forced to launch systematic monitoring of price stability to prevent the risks of unjustified price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting to regulators on a daily basis so that authorities know exactly who, when and why is initiating price increases.
The key factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the huge capital outflow, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population to foreign currency, as well as the embargo on the import of food goods from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures were kept under control, the cost of a basket of minimum-nutrition items would not have jumped 12% in just one quarter.
The ban on food imports triggered a supply shock on the domestic market and led to a perfectly logical increase in the final value.
Since we are not able to fully launch the import substitution mechanism at the current stage, as well as increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market at the expense of domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to carry the risks of an inflationary component.
If you add to this the fiscal reasons related to the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the worsening prospects for economic growth, inflation may well exceed 8% by the end of this year.
Alexander Razuvaev, director of the analytical department of "Alpari"
In the 1990s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, and in the zero years it was also higher than the current level, another thing that was then offset by rapid economic growth.
I think by the end of the year, inflation will be 8 to 8.5%.
Platon Maguta, asset manager of the Maguta Fund
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia is being successfully contained for now, but if there is further pressure, primarily on the financial sector, it may lead to certain difficulties and increase the inflationary expectations of the population, which are usually traditionally manifested in the purchase of cash currency in order to secure their savings.
It is possible to assume that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the smooth weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and by state regulation.
But the price increases traditionally start after the summer slump and may become more pronounced this fall.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to hold, as the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
Gardening centers are suffering from a decline in homeownership
