It mentions the increase in people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens, the popularity of asphalting front yards for parking and shrinking garden sizes as other factors threatening the industry, which is estimated to have annual sales of £5 billion.
Greater London, where homeownership has fallen from 61 percent to 43 percent in six years, has the lowest level of spending on garden products per household in the UK.
HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society have reported that renting housing and not having a garden space does not mean people cannot grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief gardening adviser at RHS, said: "Containing plants, for example, is especially popular with tenants who can carry plants with them when they move".
The HTA report identified the period between 1997 and 2005 as the "golden age" of retail gardening goods as a result of increased homeownership and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
It also predicts that the market will improve this year thanks to better weather after the adverse conditions in March and April last year.
