China 's biggest companies have banded together against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China's largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networking, messaging, etc.) and Baidu (China's largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
But catching up with the Chinese internet miracle, which has outpaced even its American rivals eBay and Amazon.com, will be difficult.
The Union of the Largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, with Wanda owning 70 percent and 15 percent each of the internet companies, according to Wanda Group.
The company is planned to be registered in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu's search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with about 438 million users), Tencent and the Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, the Wanda Group manages at least 49 commercial real estate properties across China and 40 shopping centers.
Last year , the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $ 8 billion) in the construction of a movie studio and a theme park in Qingdao (a city in eastern China on the shores of the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and bring in $ 960 million in revenue.
Wanda also owns the American movie theater chain AMC Entertainment Holdings, making it the largest movie theater operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its shopping malls, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by the newly created rival Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will lead the new company, the merger will increase Wanda's e-commerce user base from 40 million to 100 million by next year.
The new platform is set to become the world's largest online-to-offline platform, Dun Tse said.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract online shoppers to come to the regular offline stores or to purchase other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the biggest cake in online commerce", said Wanda's head, Wang Jianlin (quoted by Bloomberg).
"There is no real O2O platform in China right now, and in this situation, everyone has about the same chance", he believes.
China's e-commerce market is the largest in the world, and McKinsey & Co. estimates that its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has risen to 632 million, according to official statistics from Bloomberg, more than any other country in the world, except India.
And by 2015, that number is projected to grow to 850 million.
The Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huateng was until recently the richest man in China, but according to Bloomberg's billionaires index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already surpassed him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma's net worth is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu CEO Robin Lee is currently ranked third among China's richest people, while Wanda's Wang Jianlin is ranked fourth.
"It's an interesting battle to watch: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge the even richer", said Cao Lei, director of the China Center for E-Commerce Research in Hangzhou, according to Bloomberg.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to compete with Alibaba in earnest once it's established: "Rome wasn't built in a day".
It is not easy to compete with Alibaba not only for new companies but also for the world's established leaders in online commerce, according to Alibaba's latest quarterly financial report.
Alibaba is often described as something between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company earned more than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba's net profit for the period is almost double the similar sum of competitors - it has grown almost three times year-on-year and amounted to $1.99 billion.
"Alibaba still has a huge money-generating potential, in large part thanks to its mobile apps", commented an analyst from Hong Kong's Arete Research Service on the Bloomberg report.
According to the updated Alibaba prospectus on the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission's website, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July was 188 million, significantly higher than the March figure of 163 million.
And 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the last quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba is going to announce the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts polled by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of the shares.
According to Bloomberg, Alibaba's debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) is likely to take place on September 16.
The company's road show preceding the event will kick off on September 3.
Alibaba's IPO is expected to be a record in NYSE history and will raise about $20 billion.
Until now, the record for the amount of funds raised on U.S. exchanges belonged to the Visa payment system, which in 2008 held its initial public offering, earning $17.9 billion.
