Construction estimates in Russia will be calculated in a new way
The Federal Antimonopoly Service has a special oversight of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, and networking.
The FAS has created an expert council on the development of competition in the construction sector.
At its meeting, the head of the Housing and Communities Administration, Construction and Natural Resources Control Department of the FAS Vadim Solovyov stated that "today's calculation of the construction facilities' estimate is absolutely incomprehensible".
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to unjustified construction costs, the FAS believes.
And they propose that the cost of building public property at the design stage should be determined on the basis of market prices of constructive solutions instead of the current estimates and single estimates for technological operations.
These proposals are on the roadmap and are currently under consideration at the Ministry of Construction.
"The replacement of traditional construction estimates with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry", Vadim Solovyov explained to RGB.
Because the estimate now includes every bolt and nut, and it is not always possible to check everything, sometimes unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors" in the documentation.
The Ministry of Defense and FAS agree.
"The first developments on the transition to the calculation of cost by structural elements are already there: methods have been developed for calculating prices for structural solutions, compiling estimates according to these indicators, - told "RGB" the head of the department of urban planning and architecture of the Ministry of construction Elena Zhukova.
Road construction is selected as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
According to the head of the construction company "Profi-invest" Anatoly Demyanko, the estimated standards are long outdated, but no other mechanism is offered to the business.
"As for the proposed calculations for structural elements, in practice this is difficult to implement, since the construction of buildings often uses completely different technologies", he believes.
It's no secret that the construction industry is developing largely thanks to a state order.
According to the chairman of the board of the National Enterprise "Expert community of professionals of state order" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most payable customer.
Deputy Director for Engineering of the Rosatom Capital Construction Branch Center Vladimir Malachov pointed out that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors to enter this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is as much as possible protected from someone's controlling influence.
The expert council proposed to form a state order system in such a way that the same executor is not entitled to receive more than one contract for the amount of more than 1 billion rubles. or several contracts for the amount of more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business, as well as the efficiency of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case it will be necessary to assign the customer with the functions of the general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the staff of the customer and budgetary expenses for its maintenance.
The experts of the customer must have the knowledge to assess the quality of the work carried out by the contractor and its safety.
Often, this will require determining who is responsible for the overall security of the facility.
In addition, this approach may lead to an outflow of highly qualified participants in public procurement due to the lack of interest in receiving a public order for an incomplete volume of works and a small amount of the contract.
Alexander Yevshashenkov, deputy head of the expert consultation center of the Institute of procurement, believes that the procedure of the state order has now turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And he gave this example: "the participant must indicate "specific indicators" when filling out the application without specifying the words: "or equivalent", "should be", "from", "more", "less", "analog", "or", "type", "similar type", "not lower", "lower", "higher", "can", "may have", "may be", "earlier", "not earlier", "not higher", "not allowed" etc.
Thus, customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of the contract applications submitted by the contracting entities.
Another problem of 44-FZ, according to Yevstashenkov, was the need to evaluate the quality of work through the "paper" proposal of the participant at the stage of submitting the application.
When considering the participant's application, one can really assess only the qualification of the contractor, but not the quality of the work, which has not even been started yet, - the expert believes.
The quality of the work can only be assessed when it is accepted.
The expert council also proposed moving marginal income from the top to the bottom echelon to eliminate intermediate contractors.
The Chairman of the Expert Council, the Secretary of State, the Deputy Head of the FAS, Andrei Tsarikovsky, believes that this should not be done, since the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Or it'll be like the famous reprise of Arkady Rykin's "The Atelier": "Do you have any complaints about the buttons?"
Israeli children return to school after the war in Gaza
Thousands of Israeli children in the Gaza Strip returned to school on Monday after spending a summer in bomb shelters as rockets and mines rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the area recovered from the fighting.
The start of school brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-hit settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, the staff of the "Pashosh" kindergarten, which was hit by a missile, removed the traces of debris from the walls and children's shelters before the arrival of the students.
"We are a little scared, but we are looking forward to the future", said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
A lot of kids in our neighborhood really need to get back to a normal life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said that suddenly going back to school was "a little weird".
"It was a difficult time, and we didn't leave our homes at all", she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the Gaza border to express his support.
Before a ceasefire agreement halted the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad were either not outdoors or left their homes to move to safer areas beyond the Gaza Strip to escape missile and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old Palestinian boy was killed by a shell of a landmine, are questioning whether they should return.
The Ministry of Education says about a dozen families have not returned.
Their children were sent to other schools for that time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a town on the border with Gaza that has suffered greatly from Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study hard and said: "We will do everything we can to educate you and to keep you safe".
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite ceasefire last Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately ended hostilities, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand for lifting the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and opening airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers who died in the war.
A new round of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rocket and mine rounds at Israeli cities, mostly in the south.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, conducted more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
As a result of Israeli attacks, thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip have been damaged and destroyed, and an estimated 250,000 people have found shelter in more than 100 schools that have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting raging, education officials last week postponed the start of the school year.
"I hope the school will open soon so that we can complete our education, like children all over the world and Jewish children", said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of the schools in Gaza.
