How people live in the oldest house in Ufa
In the former house of goldsmiths and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on the street of the October Revolution 57/1 (formerly the Large Kazan) 18 apartments.
The 18th-century house has remained virtually unchanged since its construction, except for its age.
Strangers come here as if on a tour, and the residents suffer more than they enjoy, from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest house in Ufa, whose walls are remembered by the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is not exact, historians indicate two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But anyway, it turns out the building is no less than 300 years old.
The old yard, the open door, the creaky stairs.
The doors are close together, the walls are cracked, and the plastered walls give the street a view.
I think we're on the same page.
And the locals say, "You don't think it is, it's true".
Living in a wooden house from the 18th century is very difficult, says Tatyana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment No. 3.
It's a state property, but the money hasn't been allocated for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits that the government has forgotten about.
The last renovation was 40 years ago.
The walls are still holding up, but the foundation is rotten.
Many residents still use the outdoor toilet and bathe in the public bathroom once a week.
How can one be satisfied in such conditions?!
The road goes right under the windows, there's not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatiana is moving the curtain.
Now you can see what you could only hear before: a stream of cars floating under the windows.
You see, the windows are always cracking, we can't open the windows, and we're used to the noise.
Man is accustomed to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still a model, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
Plus, we have two rooms, three of us and a son.
Other families have much worse conditions, with ceilings on the second floor generally just over a meter and a half high.
For the contrast, Tatiana offers to visit the neighbor from apartment No. 6 Ludmila Starostina.
A pleasant, hospitable woman offers a cup of coffee and with a sad smile tells:
We have a one-room apartment, 14.5 m2 for four people, and we live like this: with my husband and daughter and granddaughter.
I've been here since I was born, there's never been another living space - Ludmila looks around the room: an anthrax, two sofas with the letter "g"; one of them has a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very narrow and little different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historical".
But the ceiling is leaking regularly, so the plumbing system is no good.
Ludmila talks about her apartment as ordinary and surprising at the same time, like an Italian whose house stands on Roman ruins.
So it boils down to one thing that's very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The plumbing was done about 40 years ago during the last renovation.
Then they built us a little backyard kitchen and a toilet out of the old shola.
We live right where Demidov and his family lived, the servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
The real estate department in Ufa says privatization is irrelevant.
We'll only get a one-bedroom apartment anyway, we can't claim more.
Four months ago, they promised to move us out, but that's all they did.
I'm not used to complaining, and I won't.
A whole dynasty lived in this apartment: my grandparents, my mother and father, my husband and I, and my daughter and granddaughter.
Everything happened during that time.
For example, the big rats were running around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the flier, they're a meter thick!
They say the solution was mixed in the eggs, which is why it lasts so long.
The house is well built, thanks to Demidov!
Probably just so nobody's killed by a collapsed ceiling or a fence.
But the building itself is slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and timbers of the houses are rotting, the floors have repeatedly failed, we poured cement over it, but all is useless - the solution goes into the ground like a well.
They say there is a secret passageway under our room and a passage to the White River, which was specially made by the Old Believers who once lived here, so that they could hide from danger, should anything happen.
They were being followed.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how a historian came to them, begging to begin excavations in the apartment.
And then convinced them to give them a place to live in exchange for his one-bedroom apartment on Oktyabr Avenue.
Ludmila refused the historian:
Where are the four of us going?
And here there's a small hope that they'll give us more space.
If we agreed to the exchange, we wouldn't have won anything.
The Elders never won anything, though.
Lyudmila's biggest dream is to have them relocated, and her daughter and 16-year-old granddaughter given a separate room.
So two families were given a two-room apartment instead of the not-so-magnificent ruins where two generations now live.
The cute, miniature girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, her large family lives in two cramped rooms, called flats, with a total area of 23 square meters.
There were seven of us, two children.
You can see the conditions.
The fabric falls off in pieces, as do the window frames, the kitchen walls and the rooms, and the holes in the walls.
The water in the tap is only cold all year round.
If you walk through the apartments of the oldest house in Ufa, you can see that the most fortunate of all were the Lavrentievs from apartment No. 4.
They're in the most spacious rooms on the first floor.
You're right, there's plenty of room!
Room's 75 square feet, three people registered.
We live in the same rooms where, according to legend, Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentiev.
The ceilings are high, spacious.
One bad thing is, everything around me is cracking, falling apart, crumbling.
The neighbors must have told you!
The hardest part was the floors, the wooden boards rotted, the ground literally slipped from underneath our feet.
I put up the props, the wedges, the hall is still empty, and in the other room we're swinging, it's so shaky.
Alexander Dmitrievich can tell you more about the house of the merchant Evdokim Demidov than any tour guide.
He treats the goldsmith like a relative, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was extraordinary: the owner of the Kagi and Uzanka factories built houses, cast cannons and bells, kept the Ural mines.
The heirs of the merchant estate are proud of their ancestors, but they no longer want to live under the same roof as history.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the XX century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then around it stood wooden quarters for carriages, stables and guard houses, later demolished.
In 1968 they tried to move our house, but something stopped them...
The story repeated itself in 2014: they were offered new housing again.
We, as a team, gathered all the documents, went through the necessary instances, and suddenly we found out that the move to the apartments was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
We don't believe in all this anymore.
Two years ago, Lavrentiev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to find out about the fate of the house.
The tenant was not accepted by the officials.
They sent it from one table to another, and then, as a mockery, they issued a piece of paper without a signature or a stamp: "The Ministry of Culture has no objection to the displacement of tenants".
I even had the feeling that our house had long since left the city plan, because it was number 57 first, then 57A, and now 57/1.
It's like it was torn down in the '70s.
"Russian planet" appealed to the head of the sector of information and analytical work of the land resources department of Ufa Vladimir Barabash.
The house on the street of the October Revolution 57/1 is included in the program of displacement of old housing.
I can't be held responsible for the actions of the government in the 1970s, but I do know that there was a plan at the time to demolish all the old houses, despite their historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities to restore all the old houses on the street of the October Revolution, representing architectural value, is being successfully implemented.
The tenants are soon to be moved to new apartments.
According to Barabash, the restoration of the Demidov House will be carried out by Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice.
