Kenya registers civil servants to identify 'invisible workers'
Kenya has begun biometric registration of all government employees in an attempt to remove "invisible workers" from the government's payroll.
Employees who do not register within the next two weeks will no longer be paid, the government said in a statement.
The government suspects that thousands of people are still receiving salaries after leaving the civil service.
President Uhuru Kenyatta has pledged to reduce corruption in government structures after coming to power in 2013.
An audit earlier this year found that at least $1 million (£700,000) a month was lost to "invisible worker" payments and other financial irregularities.
The government suspects that salaries continue to flow into bank accounts even after a person dies or leaves the civil service, reports BBC reporter Wanyama Chebusuiri from the capital, Nairobi.
All civil servants must report to the identification centres within the next two weeks to ensure that their data is collected through biometric registration procedures, the government statement said.
Anyone who doesn't do so without good reason will be deleted from the payment ledger, it says.
"This procedure will significantly help streamline the public service by determining the actual number of public servants, and will also be used to clean up payroll at both levels of government - thus ending the problem of 'invisible workers,'" said Ann Waiguru, Cabinet Secretary for Planning and Structuring.
