One of London's most prominent developers warned that the real estate market in south-east England had "come back" to normal levels of activity.
Demand for homes in the capital has been high and prices have risen sharply, with widespread fears that the credit bubble will push the Bank of England to impose mortgage lending limits in June.
Tony Pidgley, founder and chairman of elite construction firm Berkeley, said Monday: "Since the beginning of the current fiscal year, the market has returned to the normal level of transactions from its 2013 peak", adding that this has provided a "stable working environment".
London's property market prospered during the recession as foreign buyers flocked to the capital.
Prices in the city jumped 18.5 percent last year alone, according to the Land Cadaster, significantly surpassing the 6.7 percent average for England and Wales as a whole.
Average market prices for private, affordable and student Berkeley schemes rose by about one-fifth last year, reaching £423,000 at the end of April.
However, the strengthening of the pound in recent months has made London property less attractive to foreign buyers, some of whom have also been held back by the introduction of new property taxes and political rhetoric around a potential "mansion tax" ahead of the general election next May.
London-based real estate agency Foxtons warned last week that the April mortgage market reform, which introduced tighter lending conditions, would also result in a decline in both market growth in property sales and prices in the second half of the year.
New data from the Bank of England on Monday showed a decline in the number of approved mortgage loans in June, suggesting a further cooling in the housing market.
Hamptons International, another real estate agency, cut its 2015 London property price growth forecast to 3 percent based on the fact that the real estate price sentiment has already begun to weaken.
Transaction volumes, meanwhile, fell a quarter year-on-year in London's most expensive areas, such as Chelsea, Mayfair and Kensington, according to WA Ellis.
However, the demand for homes in the capital proved very profitable for Berkeley, raising sales to over £2.2 billion.
