Just two weeks earlier, he had skied in the French Alps.
The X-ray results came back.
It was mesothelioma, an incurable cancer that affects the pleura, or lining of the lungs.
For most cancers, it's hard to pinpoint the exact cause.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients have smoked.
But mesothelioma is different.
In almost all cases, the cause was exposure to asbestos, a fibrous building material that was once called "miracle" but is now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that can be ignored.
Asbestos, after all, is a material of the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when a recommendation for an industrial ban came into force.
Even when it was in use, only people in specific industries worked closely with it: pipe fitters, builders, carpenters, and dock workers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it's hardly a cause for concern today.
But such calm is wrong.
The UK, it turns out, is at the peak of the mesothelioma epidemic today.
More people die here from mesothelioma than in any other country on the planet.
With an annual death rate of about 2,500, more than twice as many people die from the disease as from car accidents.
Annual number of mesothelioma deaths since 1980 and projected future deaths in the UK
The reason we're feeling its lethal effects now is that while asbestos use has been illegal for many years (all types of asbestos were eventually banned by law in 1999), it usually takes decades to develop mesothelioma.
And mesothelioma is not limited to veterans of the construction industry.
Asbestos was, and in many cases still is, a byproduct of the houses we live in, the offices we work in, the schools we study in, and the stores we shop in.
As a result, mesothelioma does not pay attention to class, income, occupation, or age.
The bastions of the elite, from the fashionable London department stores to private schools, turned out to be no salvation.
The parliament building is strewn with asbestos.
Even hospitals designed to treat us have turned out to be reservoirs of this deadly carcinogen.
Andrew Lawson was not old.
He wasn't a pipefitter.
In fact, he had to think about where he might have come into contact with asbestos.
Then he figured it out.
"It seems there may have been a lot of asbestos in the tunnels at Guy's Hospital, where I spent six years as an intern", he wrote.
Everyone - students, nurses, doctors, and truckers - used these tunnels.
I wonder how many of my peers have the same disease.
That was a question that, unfortunately, he could only partially answer.
"Of the four doctors who had been trained at Guy's Hospital and who had subsequently developed mesothelioma in the last five years", he noted in a letter in 2010, "I am the only one left alive".
How many of us get it?
Andrew Lawson was diagnosed with mesothelioma when he was 48.
When he died, on February 17th of this year, he was 55.
It's unusual to live that long.
Fifty percent of mesothelioma patients die within eight months of diagnosis.
It's always deadly.
So now we can just repeat Lawson's question: "How many of us have the same disease?"
According to Professor Julian Pito, the UK's leading expert on mesothelioma, the most likely estimate is that between 1970 and 2050, when the asbestos epidemic in the UK is due to end, some 90,000 people will die.
Most people don't realize they're going to die like this.
Asbestos mine in Quebec, Canada Alamy
A quick look at courtroom records, where victims often seek compensation, shows how far the mesothelioma attack has spread.
This June, for example, Marks & Spencer admitted to exposing Janice Ellen to asbestos in an uncontrolled manner.
She worked at the chain for nine years, from 1978 to 1987, running the clothing departments at two sites, one of which was a flagship store on Oxford Street.
Mrs. Ellen was only 18 when she started at M&S.
She has two children now in their 20s.
"Before that", she says, "I had never heard of mesothelioma, and I hardly knew about asbestos.
I never thought it would affect me.
Few people really know much about asbestos.
Asbestos is not a single substance but a group of six minerals.
They get their name from the word "asbestosform", which means a fibrous structure that gives them strength and flexibility.
Of these six, three were commonly used in construction.
Chrysotile, commonly known as white asbestos, is much more common in buildings today.
It's been used in roof panels, floor tiles, pipe insulation, boiler seams, even in the brake pads of cars.
It is less deadly than other forms of asbestos, but it is still recognized by the European Union and the World Health Organization as a "serious source of health damage" that can lead to death.
However, brown asbestos (amozite) and blue asbestos (crocodile oil) are more dangerous.
Britain was once the world's largest importer of brown asbestos, and experts suggest that "there is strong, though indirect, evidence to suggest that it is the main cause of the exceptionally high number of mesothelioma cases [in Britain]".
A Marks & Spencer employee was exposed to asbestos at the company's flagship store in Oxford Street, London Alamy.
