Genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
The British woman said she spent many years thinking she was going to die after being misdiagnosed.
Caryn Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, a group of inherited disorders that cause nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
CMT UK charity reports that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with MS because so little is known about the condition.
Some 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have PTSD, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, unsteady gait and cramped toes.
Patients may experience numbness or pain, and the condition is not cured and progresses, meaning that symptoms get worse over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedrichs Ataxia, a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she'd be wheelchair bound by the time she was 18, and dead by the time she was 30.
The 51-year-old mother of two said: "As a child, I knew I couldn't do what others could.
I was falling every day, and it took me more time to do it.
I could never skate or skate with other children, and I was often teased at school for the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to loosen her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at her medical records when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
"I felt guilty because I was in the wrong place, so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about the condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association", she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic that could be imagined.
I thought I'd be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in the meantime.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she had thought, and she asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me, and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease, because you'd be in a wheelchair by now".
I think you have something that's much less of a threat to life.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have TBI.
"When he explained what the MTS was, I thought I pulled out a lucky ticket", she said.
