A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and more jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country have increased moderately over the past year as the recovery has accelerated, according to a new study released last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local treasuries in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden on state and local businesses last year increased by 4.3 percent to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and this was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years of declining bills in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes are up faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study by a professional services firm, Ernst & Young, and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56 percent, is from business taxes, while Maryland's tax revenue is 36 percent from corporations.
Virginia, at 28 percent, brings in the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the increase in tax revenue is driven by a return to the previous level of value of corporate real estate, the researchers say, which has raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row when growth was less than 1 percent.
While a large share of this revenue is coming from big states like California, New York and Texas, it seems that the same is happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia paid a combined $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, up $9.6 billion from 2012, a 4.2 percent increase from the year before.
However, the observed return on property value has no similar effect on the growth of state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of corporate tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of their state and local taxes in the form of property taxes.
"What's happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned by either the government or a nonprofit that doesn't pay property taxes", said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Taxation Center.
So Maryland has to rely much more on, say, income taxes to pay for the same services that other states have.
The recent rise in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurial incomes also seem to be improving, according to this data.
Companies in the region filed $2.3 billion in statewide corporate income taxes, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although trends are in one direction, the tax burden on local entrepreneurs is not increasing at the same rate in all three areas.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was the same as the national average, 4.3 percent, while the growth rate in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia saw a lower-than-average increase in tax revenues of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax rate of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), at 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for entrepreneurs at the state and local levels and, in general, a more favorable tax climate for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county wasn't evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just like Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to as high as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be feeling better and thus paying more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
The taxes on entrepreneurs paid as individual income taxes by small business owners - the transitional structure under which most small firms are structured - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, a much faster rate of growth than the taxes on women entrepreneurs overall.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with state and local government turnover tax revenue up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may be lagging behind as the decline in federal spending is affecting the labor market in the region.
