Royal Blood's debut album is a new hope for British rock, taking the rock duo from clubs to stadiums.
Royal Blood have been on the scene for just over a year, but they've already been nominated for a BBC Music Award, a warm-up tour with Arctic Monkeys and a visit to the New York concert set from Jimmy Page himself.
Their eponymous debut album had received 100,000 pre-orders a few months before its release, and the contract for its release is in the portfolio of major label Warner Music.
Given the current sad state of the music industry, it's a very unusual situation, because this is not the new Lana Del Rey or the new R'n'B with the sweet voice, but a duo of British bull-looking guys playing with the same level of volume and intensity that was last in fashion a couple of decades ago.
In general, the stakes on the first album in connection with all the above circumstances were particularly high and already quite justified.
The duo has made a name for themselves that could only be attacked by desperate metal hairy men, and the blood of kings seems to be in their veins, too.
It's, of course, above all, the heroes of Led Zeppelin's past: like the great quartet, Royal Blood are aiming to shake up the stagnant blood of British rock, taking it to new heights.
It's too early to predict the success of this venture, but there are some things we can say.
Ten songs in thirty-two minutes is not so much a demonstration of phenomenal compositional talent as a confident and powerful declaration of intent.
Some of the merits of individual songs, of course, cannot be denied: say, the pilot single "Out Of The Black" is characterized by being remembered not by the melodic line, but by the drum part.
Musicians joke that this song is easier to play than to sing.
Also noteworthy is the powerful "Little Monster" and the closing track "Better Strangers" with a Shakespearean quote in the title.
The truth is, though, that each of these songs will sound great at a heavy rock party, but when played back-to-back, they merge into a more or less homogeneous canvas.
And that's not necessarily a bad thing, it's the opposite.
The strength of Royal Blood is that they don't claim the praise of the new Lennon and McCartney (rather aiming at Motörhead's successors), but have brought out numerous rock duos from the ghettos of indie clubs.
Their music, though somewhat varied, is made for stadiums, in a room of less than a couple thousand people, obviously cramped.
The secret lies in part in the clever use of the bass, which replaced the guitar in the familiar format invented by the early zero The White Stripes.
But it's not just the instruments, it's the way you write the songs.
The retro-rock zero heroes had a hard time moving beyond the postmodern paradigm, reluctantly recognizing themselves as not just epigones, but independent creative units.
Royal Blood sounds so powerful and bold that it successfully strips away some of the secondary and hard-boiled material.
After all, who says rock has to be smart?
