Deputies suggested speeding up the entry into force of the Personal Data Law
If the initiative is successful, Russian data will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
The draft law, which provides for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians, was introduced in the State Duma from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is located in the legislative base of the lower chamber.
It was written by the State Duma deputies Vadim Degengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parahin ("Justice Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
This change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to more prompt and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the protection of personal data and the observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, which parliamentarians are rushing to enact, obliges to store personal data of Russians processed through the Internet on the territory of the Russian Federation.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, store, clarify and extract personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as to indicate the location of such databases.
In addition, the law grants Roskomnadzor the right to restrict access to information processed in violation of the Russian legislation in the field of personal data on the basis of a court decision.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of offending sites - an automated information system called the "Register of violators of the rights of subjects of personal data".
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoy and Vadim Denganin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party of the Russian Federation.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who don't have data centers in Russia will have to pay rent
Commenting on the draft law introduced today in the State Duma, first deputy chairman of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said he saw no problem in postponing the date of the entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own personal data storage of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers in lease and already provides their servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies that today already provide their servers".
"There are also several independent data centers willing to cooperate in this area", he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I don't see any problems - they will get technological opportunities for placement", Levin concluded.
The controversial bill
Immediately after the bill was published, the Russian Electronic Communications Association expressed concern that if the bill was passed, Russians would no longer be able to use many global internet services.
In particular, it is about online booking of air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data by determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
The RAEC's statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism to inform the user where the recording is being made, systematizing his personal data.
In this case, the person can choose the territory where the actions will be carried out.
The adoption of similar bills to "localise" personal data in other countries has led to the departure of global services and significant economic losses.
