However, when it comes to films aimed at a slightly older audience, it seems that the problem is not necessarily the quality of the films themselves.
In July, Entertainment Weekly compared the average CinemaScore and Metacritic ratings of every film released in the summer of at least 2,000 copies between the May Memorial Day holiday and July 20, 2013 and this year.
The results, which take into account the opinions of both filmgoers and critics, suggest that this year's film crop is similar in caliber to last year's hits.
Some commentators suggest that it may be due to changing viewing habits and the growing popularity of streaming Internet services such as Netflix.
Director John Favreau, who is currently working on the upcoming Disney film The Jungle Book, told the Hollywood Reporter website: "I think times are changing".
We have to accept that and not try to chase what was before.
In contrast to the current drop in Hollywood box office receipts, Netflix's revenue from streaming services reached $1.2 billion, almost double last year's figure of $837 million.
Last summer, director Steven Spielberg criticized the studios for relying too heavily on comic book franchises, and predicted the "crash" of Hollywood.
In light of the current downturn, some commentators claim that there was some truth to his gloomy predictions.
With several potential box office hits expected to be released in the summer of 2015, including Avengers: Age of Ultron, Minyonov and Jurassic Park, other filmmakers are more optimistic.
"X-Men" producer Simon Kinberg recently called the fall in box office receipts simply "cyclical", telling the Hollywood Reporter: "Next summer will be the biggest box office summer in history, and nobody's going to worry about it".
