The sanctioned menu
On August 6, President Vladimir Putin signed a decree on the application of certain economic measures to ensure Russia's security, which are called mainly food sanctions.
Importation of beef, pork, poultry meat and offal, meat delicacies, fish, shellfish, milk, yogurt, cheese, vegetables, fruit, nuts, sausages and sugar syrups is prohibited.
Restaurants have begun to compete with suppliers: the prices of food have risen, and it is urgent to look for analogues from other countries.
The most affected are the expensive restaurants with single-kitchens in France, Italy, Spain, which were supplied directly from the "mother" countries.
The whole thing's been rebuilt before.
For example, when the Federal Agricultural Inspection Service banned the import of Australian beef in early 2014, and the year before that, American and Canadian beef.
In return, suppliers have arranged for beef supplies from Argentina, Uruguay and New Zealand.
But the summer of 2014 sanctions turned out to be much more serious.
True, on August 20, Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev approved amendments to the presidential decree that removed from the ban the Atlantic salmon and trout, lactose-free milk, seed potatoes, sugar corn, peas and onions for sowing.
Valerio, the Italian, hopes that sanctions can be eased further.
