"Euro-protocol" instead of the GIDD reference
Casco payments will be available without a GIDD certificate - the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of the "euro protocol" in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed a draft directive according to which, from September 1 of this year, insured motorists will be able to get cash payments without a GIDD certificate.
It is true that we are talking only about cases where the accident was registered according to the "Euro protocol" without the involvement of the traffic police.
That is, if only two cars were involved in the accident, no physical injuries were sustained, the damage was within the limit and both drivers agreed on who was to blame.
From August 2, the limit of payments under the "euro-protocol" is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1 in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in Moscow and Leningrad regions it will be increased to 400 thousand rubles.
The point is that often, even with minor injuries, in a situation where an accident can be registered under the "Euro protocol", the drivers who have been involved in an accident call the DPS.
Because if you had a casco policy, you couldn't get compensation without a D.I.R.D. certificate.
The parameters prescribed in the draft directive are designed to eliminate this obstacle to the implementation of the "Euro-protocol" in Russia.
According to them, the maximum casco payment for an accident that is not paid by the DIGD should not be lower than the limit of the "Euro Protocol".
However, it cannot be more than the limit specified in the casco insurance contract.
The idea is certainly useful and could theoretically relieve both road and traffic officials.
But it's not likely to please motorists or insurance companies.
The latter are already talking about the serious threat of increasing fraud, which could result from the introduction of new rules on casco payments.
As for drivers, it's hard to imagine what work will have to be done to overcome the inherent Russian conservatism.
In most cases, the driver will wait for hours for the inspector to report a minor accident, because that's more reliable.
And it's not clear which will be easier - defeating the fraudsters or convincing drivers of the reliability of the Euro Protocol.
The savings certificate will be made anonymous and irrevocable
The Treasury wants to ban the deposit-only savings certificates, but it's going to allow banks to make them the equivalent of a deposit.
The Treasury is drafting a bill that would ban the use of savings certificates.
The instrument has recently become popular, as rates are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that the savings certificates for the depositor do not fit into the deposit insurance system, and the bank is cheaper, because you do not have to make any transfers to the deposit insurance agency (ASV).
The point is that this move is planned because of the small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and Sberbank and Bank of Moscow, which, according to the ASV, control 98% of the market, will suffer.
The Bank of Moscow's share, according to the agency's calculations, is about 3.5%.
The problem, the FSA explains, is that customers of a small bank who buy such a certificate, if their license is revoked, try to get money in the FSA.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying proof-of-concept savings certificates, may assume that their deposits are insured.
The justified lack of insurance payments for these certificates in the event of a bank license revocation can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the agency's practice, there have been cases when holders of pre-emptive certificates have tried to collect insurance compensation through the court", the agency said.
The problem, of course, is made up.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of the certificates anyway, because they have no right to compensation from the state.
If the instrument were not insured by the SBA, metal accounts would be banned along with it, where citizens' funds are recorded in grams of one of four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
These accounts are not covered by the deposit insurance system either, but they are not being compromised.
The fact is, it's likely that the certificate of origin is a very convenient security that can actually act as a quasi-negotiator.
At the same time, their movement is almost uncontrollable: any customer of the bank can buy a certificate, give it to any citizen, and before cashing such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no accident that the bill stipulates that a savings certificate must be a registered security, which must be kept in a depository.
And to make the banks sweeter, they're allowed to issue these certificates without the right to early repayment.
So, we're introducing the kind of deposit-free money that bankers have been dreaming about for a long time.
