Germany to send 30 anti-tank systems to Iraq
Germany will supply weapons to Iraq to counter the militants of the terrorist group "Islamic State", reports ITAR-TASS on August 31 with reference to the decision taken at the meeting of the representatives of the German government headed by Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Germany is reported to be sending 30 Milan anti-tank missiles and 500 rounds of ammunition to Iraq, as well as 8,000 G3 and G36 assault rifles.
Deliveries will be made by the end of September.
In addition, it was decided to allocate another 50 million euros to Iraq for humanitarian aid.
On 1 September, Ms. Merkel will make a government statement on the subject in the Bundestag.
Germany has not yet deployed its weapons to hot spots.
The opinions of the people of Germany on the issue of sending weapons to Iraqis are divided.
Some believe that this is the only way to stop ISIS fighters, while others fear that these weapons could eventually fall into the hands of terrorists.
