Teenagers picked up in a helicopter from the Blue Mountains
TWO teenage bushwalkers were flown to safety by helicopter after spending the night stranded in the Blue Mountains of New South Wales.
A 16-year-old girl and an 18-year-old man went on a hike shortly after noon Sunday at Govets Leap in Blackheath.
Concerned relatives called the police around 8pm when they did not return home.
A search party was dispatched, including local police and a rescue team, and the pair were found around 11pm near Bridal Vale Falls.
The girl hurt her knee, and the young man fell and hit his head.
Officers stayed with the couple overnight, and they were picked up on a lever Monday morning.
They were taken by ambulance in stable condition to Blue Mountains Hospital.
Two unions have met
The Minsk summit did not resolve the problems for which it was convened, but it did give birth to a new format: the first leaders of the European Union met with the first leaders of the future of the Eurasian Economic Union.
Even if it was a worrying issue (the situation around Ukraine is not tolerating delays), the leaders of the EU and the Customs Union discussed a number of "hot issues" for the first time.
Whether such a structure is capable of working effectively is unclear; however, it is clear who took the cream off this summit.
Questions about this fell away on the evening of August 26, when Belarusians, and then other Eurasians and Europeans saw the new president Lukashenko in the television news.
The Belarusian leader showed an example of fine courtesy, it was the behavior of a man who just broke the jackpot - and is planning a decent old age in the higher society.
How the Maidan helped Lukashenko
The arrival in Minsk of three major European commissioners (EU ministers) who met with Lukashenko and allowed him to speak at the final briefing on their behalf - is not just legitimization of the president with 20 years of experience.
This is a request for recognition of Minsk as a full-fledged subject of European politics and the main mediator of the Ukrainian crisis.
Senior analyst of the Belarusian Institute for Strategic Studies Denis Melyantsov is confident that Brussels will no longer be able to talk to Minsk in the same tone as before.
"The fact that Catherine Ashton met with Lukashenko gives us grounds to believe that relations with the EU will continue to thaw", he told "Ogyenk".
This iceberg has a hidden part: the Belarusian authorities began preparing for the breakthrough long before the November Maidan in Kiev - in the summer of 2013.
"Results were achieved with the EU - successful negotiations on visa facilitation and readmission, dialogue on modernization, - lists the interlocutor of "Ogyenka", - and negotiations on international security were held with the United States.
The States even lifted some sanctions.
As for the Ukrainian events, they themselves and the reaction of the Belarusian leadership to them only fueled this process.
Minsk, on the one hand, managed to keep relations with Ukraine warm enough not to lose much in mutual trade, and President Poroshenko could come to Belarus for negotiations.
On the other hand, the Belarusian leader, who de jure did not recognize the annexation of Crimea to Russia and called for punishing pro-Russian militias in the Donbass with all severity, did not quarrel with Moscow.
Minsk has not left the Customs Union or the CSTO, and a Russian airbase is located in Baranowice.
Brussels and Washington have noted Minsk's balanced position on the Ukrainian issue - and have assessed it, Belarusian experts are confident.
The extent to which Lukashenko's move towards political diversification will be successful will be seen by how often Minsk will be able to host meetings in the EU+TS format in the near future.
The press service of the EU High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Diplomacy, Catherine Ashton, was unable to respond promptly to questions about what Brussels expects from the new format of relations.
Ashton's press secretary, Maya Kosyanch, only told "Ognika" that this topic is not a priority in the context of resolving issues of war and peace.
There were reports that Kazakhstan could be the next venue for the meeting on the Ukrainian issue with the participation of the first persons in the new format.
The key to Minsk was the statement of President Nursultan Nazarbayev, in which he admitted that he was personally asked to do so by representatives of the European Union.
However, at the final briefing, Alexander Lukashenko made it clear that all sides are not against Minsk remaining the central platform for meetings in the format of Russia-OSCE-Ukraine, as well as at the level of heads of state and high representatives of the European Commission.
This means that the "last dictator of Europe" is given the status of a fully-fledged European leader who is helping to solve a global problem.
Best friend of the European farmer.
The EU delegation, which included the European Commissioners for Trade and Energy, had already pushed to the conclusion that the main undercurrent of the summit was not the tragic situation in the Donbass, but the economy.
Indeed, the timetable for future gas talks and the EU-Ukraine Association Agreement looks more ambitious than peace declarations without specific dates or figures.
Trade Commissioner Karl De Gjucht, however, noted that EU representatives "came to Minsk to seek a solution to the political crisis, which has economic consequences, not the other way around".
However, it seems that the crisis in Ukraine is also working for Belarus.
Its consequences - and first and foremost the mutual sanctions imposed by the West and Russia - give Minsk, which is currently under sanctions pressure, a long-awaited space for maneuver.
According to the head of the Mises Research Center, ex-candidate to the presidency of Belarus Yaroslav Romanchuk, European investors are actively interested in the possibilities of Belarus for the supply of agricultural products to the Russian Federation in circumvention of sanctions.
At the same time, supply schemes are being put forward, for which Vladimir Putin at the summit has angered Minsk.
"The initiators of these schemes, - Romance emphasized "Ogenku", - are not Belarusian businessmen, but Russian companies.
They've been working on schemes for long time to supply goods, including from Poland, Germany, Lithuania, and today those schemes are broken.
Russian business is in dire need of somehow restoring them, even through the mediation of Belarusian structures.
The second scenario, - continues the expert, - is related to the fact that many Ukrainian companies are willing to establish production in Belarus from Ukrainian raw materials also with a focus on the Russian market.
Ukrainian producers have about $4 billion in exports to Russia, and Belarusian production and trade schemes may now be in high demand".
According to Romanchuk, the role of the host of the EU and the TC negotiations is ideal for Lukashenko and from the point of view of developing economic ties with Europe.
He recalls that the losses of the EU's agricultural sector from Moscow's sanctions are estimated at 5-10 billion euros, while the European Commission has currently offered only 125 million euros in compensation to farmers.
The Belarusian president could propose that Brussels work together to minimize the consequences for European farmers.
This could raise Lukashenko's authority in the EU to an unprecedented height.
