Anger has turned out to be the most universal and functional emotion of man .
Angry facial expressions are biologically universal to humans, and each organ and muscle group involved in their creation is not random, but an additional means of expressing power and threat, researchers from Australia and the United States found.
Their findings were reported in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and a brief summary of their findings can be found in a press release from the University of California, Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expressions - downward-turning eyebrows, thin lips, and puffy nostrils - are the same in all cultures, and are made by children who are blind from birth and have never seen them, notes lead author Aaron Sell.
In a large research project on the nature of anger, scientists found that anger was a key factor in effective conflict management.
The more physical damage one person can do to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his own terms, and he conveys this to the other person through anger.
The researchers also found evidence for another hypothesis: Physically strong people are more likely to be angry and violent, feel entitled to impose unfair conditions on others, and prefer violent conflict resolution to peaceful ones.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining", the researchers decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that produce the angry facial expression should represent the angry individual as more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the other person - and thus force him to agree to his terms as soon as possible to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers modeled faces on a computer where each of the seven elements of an angry face were present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although a lowered eyebrow or a raised chin alone did not make the face look ugly, the study participants were unanimous in their recognition that a person with such features was physically stronger.
Human anger, like animal anger, is a threat: an exaggerated display of power that forces consent and submission.
A human inflates his nostrils and clenches his lips for the same purpose as a frog inflating itself or a baboon displaying its fangs.
"Anger is triggered by the refusal of the other person to accept the situation, and the face immediately takes on a form that demonstrates the consequences of that refusal to the other side as effectively as possible.
