Ministry of Communications offered to allocate 250 million rubles to the "Crimea" TV and radio company
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget to the autonomous non-profit organization "Crimea" Teleradio Company".
This is stated in the draft government resolution prepared by the department, which "Lenta.ru" has read.
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the social and economic situation and the development of modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment".
In particular, the money is intended to re-equip the hardware-studio block, video walls, central hardware and video server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
The company will also use the money to pay for the use of fiber-optic communication lines (FOPLs) and for repairs to the energy system.
The subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget, provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state-run TV and radio broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
Today, the television signal of the TV and radio company covers more than 75 percent of the peninsula.
In 2011, the "Crimea" TV company received a license to broadcast in digital format.
